Below is a **complete, self‑contained example** that shows how to expose a C++ iterator from *libpcapng* to OCaml.  
It contains:

* `pcapng.mli` – the public OCaml interface that a user will see.  
* `pcapng_stubs.cpp` – the C‑C++ glue code that implements the binding.  

You can drop the two files into a small project, compile the stub with a C++ compiler, and link it with the OCaml runtime.  The example is deliberately simple (it only walks the file and calls a user‑supplied OCaml function for each frame) but it contains all the pieces you need to extend it further (e.g. expose the iterator itself, add more fields, etc.).

---

## 1️⃣  `pcapng.mli` – public OCaml API

```ocaml
(* ----------------------------------------------------------------------
   pcapng.mli   –  OCaml interface for libpcapng
   ---------------------------------------------------------------------- *)

(** {1 Types} *)

(** A captured network frame.  Only a few of the many fields that *libpcapng*
    can provide are wrapped here – you can add more later if you need them. *)
type frame = {
  ts_sec      : float;   (** timestamp, seconds since the epoch *)
  data        : bytes;   (** raw packet bytes (captured_len long) *)
  original_len: int;     (** length of the original packet on the wire *)
  captured_len: int;     (** length that was actually captured *)
}

(** {1 Exceptions} *)

(** Raised when libpcapng reports an error (e.g. file not found,
    malformed file, etc.). The error message from the C++ library is
    attached as a string payload. *)
exception Error of string

(** {1 Main entry point} *)

(** [iter_frames filename ~f] opens the pcapng file named [filename] and
    calls [f] for each frame that the underlying C++ iterator yields.
    The order is exactly the order in the file.

    The callback may raise; the iteration stops and the exception is
    propagated to the caller.

    @raise Error if the file cannot be opened or if libpcapng reports a
    problem while parsing. *)
val iter_frames : filename:string -> f:(frame -> unit) -> unit
```

*Why this design?*  

* The user never touches the C++ iterator – they simply provide a callback
  that is invoked for each frame.  This matches the “run a piece of their own
  code for each frame” requirement.  
* The `frame` record is a **plain OCaml value**, so the callback runs at full
  speed without any extra indirection.  
* Errors are turned into a regular OCaml exception (`Error`) so they can be
  caught with `try … with`.  

---

## 2️⃣  `pcapng_stubs.cpp` – C/C++ glue

```cpp
/* ----------------------------------------------------------------------
   pcapng_stubs.cpp   –  C/C++ stubs for the OCaml binding
   ---------------------------------------------------------------------- */

#include <caml/mlvalues.h>
#include <caml/memory.h>
#include <caml/alloc.h>
#include <caml/callback.h>
#include <caml/fail.h>
#include <caml/custom.h>
#include <caml/signals.h>
#include <caml/bigarray.h>
#include <caml/threads.h>

#include <string>
#include <exception>

// ----------------------------------------------------------------------
// 1.  The real libpcapng API (replace these includes with the real ones)
// ----------------------------------------------------------------------
// (In a real project you would #include <libpcapng/pcapng.hpp> or similar.)
//
// For the purpose of this self‑contained example we fake a tiny subset
// of the library.  The code below can be removed once you link against the
// real library.
#include <vector>
#include <cstdint>
struct PcapNgFrame {
    double   ts_sec;          // timestamp (seconds)
    std::vector<uint8_t> data; // raw bytes
    uint32_t original_len;
    uint32_t captured_len;
};
class PcapNgFile {
public:
    explicit PcapNgFile(const std::string& filename) {
        // In the real library you would open & parse the file.
        // Here we just fake two frames for demonstration.
        if (filename.empty())
            throw std::runtime_error("empty filename");
        // fake frame 1
        PcapNgFrame f1;
        f1.ts_sec = 1.234;
        f1.original_len = 64;
        f1.captured_len = 64;
        f1.data.assign(64, 0xAA);
        frames.push_back(f1);
        // fake frame 2
        PcapNgFrame f2;
        f2.ts_sec = 2.345;
        f2.original_len = 128;
        f2.captured_len = 100;
        f2.data.assign(100, 0x55);
        frames.push_back(f2);
    }
    const std::vector<PcapNgFrame>& get_frames() const { return frames; }
private:
    std::vector<PcapNgFrame> frames;
};
// ----------------------------------------------------------------------
// End of fake libpcapng API
// ----------------------------------------------------------------------

// ----------------------------------------------------------------------
// 2.  Helpers to raise the OCaml [Error] exception
// ----------------------------------------------------------------------
static value * caml_pcapng_error_exn = nullptr;   // filled at init time

static void raise_error(const std::string& msg)
{
    if (caml_pcapng_error_exn == nullptr) {
        // Fallback – should never happen because we register the exception
        caml_failwith(msg.c_str());
    }
    caml_raise_with_string(*caml_pcapng_error_exn, msg.c_str());
}

// ----------------------------------------------------------------------
// 3.  The OCaml <-> C++ bridge
// ----------------------------------------------------------------------

// The OCaml record layout for type [frame] (see pcapng.mli)
//   0 : ts_sec      (float)
//   1 : data        (bytes)
//   2 : original_len (int)
//   3 : captured_len (int)
#define Frame_tag 0          // we use a normal block (no custom ops)
#define Frame_size 4

extern "C" CAMLprim value caml_pcapng_iter_frames(value v_filename,
                                                value v_callback)
{
    CAMLparam2(v_filename, v_callback);
    CAMLlocal1(v_frame);          // will hold the OCaml frame record

    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    // Convert OCaml string -> std::string
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    const char *c_fname = String_val(v_filename);
    std::string fname(c_fname);

    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    // Open the pcapng file (C++ side).  Any exception is turned into [Error].
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    PcapNgFile *file = nullptr;
    try {
        file = new PcapNgFile(fname);
    } catch (const std::exception& ex) {
        raise_error(std::string("open: ") + ex.what());
    } catch (...) {
        raise_error("open: unknown C++ exception");
    }

    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    // Iterate over frames.  For each frame we allocate an OCaml record
    // and invoke the user callback.
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    const std::vector<PcapNgFrame>& frames = file->get_frames();
    for (const PcapNgFrame& f : frames) {
        // --- 1. Allocate the OCaml record ---------------------------------
        v_frame = caml_alloc(Frame_size, Frame_tag);

        // ts_sec (float)
        Store_field(v_frame, 0, caml_copy_double(f.ts_sec));

        // data (bytes) – we allocate a mutable OCaml string and copy the bytes
        value v_bytes = caml_alloc_string(f.captured_len);
        memcpy(String_val(v_bytes), f.data.data(), f.captured_len);
        Store_field(v_frame, 1, v_bytes);

        // original_len (int) and captured_len (int)
        Store_field(v_frame, 2, Val_int(f.original_len));
        Store_field(v_frame, 3, Val_int(f.captured_len));

        // --- 2. Call the OCaml callback -----------------------------------
        // The callback may raise; we let the exception propagate out.
        caml_callback(v_callback, v_frame);
        // If the user pressed Ctrl‑C or other signals, be nice and poll:
        caml_check_signal();
    }

    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    // Clean up C++ side
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    delete file;

    CAMLreturn(Val_unit);
}

// ----------------------------------------------------------------------
// 4.  Register the custom exception name so that OCaml can refer to it.
// ----------------------------------------------------------------------
extern "C" CAMLprim value caml_pcapng_initialize(value unit)
{
    CAMLparam1(unit);
    // Register the exception under the name "Pcapng.Error"
    caml_pcapng_error_exn = caml_named_value("Pcapng.Error");
    if (caml_pcapng_error_exn == nullptr) {
        // If the name is not yet registered we register it now.
        // This will be visible to OCaml as [Pcapng.Error].
        static struct custom_operations dummy_ops = {
            "Pcapng.Error", NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL
        };
        caml_pcapng_error_exn = caml_alloc_custom(&dummy_ops, 0, 0, 1);
        caml_register_named_value("Pcapng.Error", caml_pcapng_error_exn);
    }
    CAMLreturn(Val_unit);
}
```

### How to compile & link

Assuming the two files live in a directory `src/`:

```bash
# 1. Build the C++ stub as a shared library
ocamlopt -output-obj -o src/pcapng_stubs.o src/pcapng_stubs.cpp \
        -ccopt -std=c++11 -ccopt -fPIC

# 2. Build the OCaml part (here we only have the .mli, so we create a tiny .ml)
cat > src/pcapng.ml <<'EOF'
(* Minimal .ml – just the external declaration and the init call *)
type frame = {
  ts_sec      : float;
  data        : bytes;
  original_len: int;
  captured_len: int;
}
exception Error of string

external iter_frames :
  filename:string -> f:(frame -> unit) -> unit = "caml_pcapng_iter_frames"

let () = Callback.register_exception "Pcapng.Error" (Error "")
let () = Callback.register "pcapng_initialize" (fun () -> 
  External.caml_pcapng_initialize)
EOF

# 3. Compile the OCaml module
ocamlopt -c src/pcapng.ml

# 4. Link everything into a native executable (replace main.ml with your own)
ocamlopt -o my_program src/pcapng.cmx src/main.ml src/pcapng_stubs.o -cclib -lstdc++
```

*If you are using `dune`, the stanza is roughly:*

```dune
(executable
 (name my_program)
 (modules main pcapng)
 (foreign_stubs
  (language cxx)
  (names pcapng_stubs))
 (libraries camlidl))   ; (or any other libs you need)
```

### What the stub does, step‑by‑step

| Step | What happens |
|------|--------------|
| **1** | Convert the OCaml `string` argument to a C++ `std::string`. |
| **2** | Open the file via `PcapNgFile`. Any C++ exception is caught and turned into the OCaml `Error` exception (via `raise_error`). |
| **3** | For every `PcapNgFrame` returned by the C++ iterator: <br> • Allocate an OCaml record (`caml_alloc`). <br> • Copy the timestamp (`caml_copy_double`). <br> • Allocate a mutable OCaml byte string (`caml_alloc_string`) and `memcpy` the packet data. <br> • Store the integer fields (`Val_int`). |
| **4** | Call the user‑supplied OCaml callback (`caml_callback`). If the callback raises, the exception propagates out of the stub, aborting the iteration. |
| **5** | After the loop, clean up the C++ object (`delete`). |
| **6** | Return `()` to OCaml. |

### Thread‑safety & signals

* The stub uses `caml_check_signal()` after each callback to make the OCaml runtime responsive to `Ctrl‑C` and other signals.  
* If you need to run the iteration in a separate OS thread you must wrap the whole stub body with `caml_acquire_runtime_system()` / `caml_release_runtime_system()`. The simple version shown here runs on the main OCaml thread.

### Extending the binding

* **Expose more fields** – add them to the `frame` record in the `.mli` and extend the stub’s `Store_field` calls.  
* **Expose the iterator itself** – allocate a custom block that holds a pointer to the C++ iterator, provide `next` and `has_next` functions, and register a finalizer that deletes the C++ object.  
* **Zero‑copy** – for very high‑throughput scenarios you can allocate a custom block that points directly at the underlying C++ buffer (using `custom_operations` with a finalizer that frees the memory).  

---

### TL;DR – What a user sees

```ocaml
open Pcapng

let print_frame f =
  Printf.printf "ts=%f len=%d data=%S\n%!"
    f.ts_sec f.captured_len
    (Bytes.sub_string f.data 0 (min 20 (Bytes.length f.data)))

let () =
  try
    iter_frames ~filename:"capture.pcapng" ~f:print_frame
  with
  | Error msg -> prerr_endline ("pcapng error: " ^ msg)
```

Running the program will invoke `print_frame` for every frame in the file, exactly as requested. The heavy lifting (parsing, iterator walking) stays in the fast C++ library, while the OCaml callback runs in the normal OCaml runtime.
